<lb corresp="#a4"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="2"/><w>m<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/></w><w>śe</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b1"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><w>yamaṣṣä<supplied>lle</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>yne</supplied>mane</w><w>nauṣ</w><w>yt<supplied>āri</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>a</supplied>lāṣmo</w><w>ka</w><w>mā</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b4"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>-nts<supplied>e</supplied></w><w>pelaiykne</w><w>a<supplied>ksaṣṣälle</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">On <ref target="http://idp.bl.uk/database/oo_loader.a4d?pm=IOL%20Toch%201121" type="external">IDP</ref>, recto and verso are reversed.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>ṣmareṃ ṣareṃ</hi>: Ogihara reads here <hi>ṣmareṃ ṣ(m)areṃ</hi>, saying that the <hi>m</hi> "may be covered by a displaced piece of paper" (<bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2011">2011</title><citedRange>119-120</citedRange></bibl>). In my view, this cannot be correct, since there is simply no piece of paper there. More likely is a mistake of the scribe, who wrote <hi>ṣma...ṣa...ṣa</hi> instead of <hi>ṣma...ṣma...ṣa</hi>. On the other hand, Ogihara's interpretation of the passage is convincing.</note></p>
         </div>
